javaslang.collection

Interface Stream<T>

  • Type Parameters:
    T - component type of this Stream
    All Superinterfaces:
    Functor<T>, HigherKinded<T,Traversable<?>>, Iterable<T>, Monad<T,Traversable<?>>, Seq<T>, Serializable, Traversable<T>, ValueObject
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    Stream.AbstractStream, Stream.Cons, Stream.Deferred, Stream.Nil

    public interface Stream<T>
extends Seq<T>, ValueObject
    A Lazy linked list implementation.
    Since:
    1.1.0

    • Nested Class Summary

      • stdin

        static Stream<String> stdin()

        Creates a Stream of strings by reading lines from the standard input System.in. The default charset is used to decode bytes to characters.

        Note: Because Stream is lazy, this method is not blocking.

        Returns:
        a new Stream of strings

      • of

        @SafeVarargs
static <T> Stream<T> of(T... elements)

        Creates a Stream of the given elements. 

           Stream.of(1, 2, 3, 4)
 = Nil.instance().prepend(4).prepend(3).prepend(2).prepend(1)
 = new Cons(1, new Cons(2, new Cons(3, new Cons(4, Nil.instance()))))
        Type Parameters:
        T - Component type of the Stream.
        Parameters:
        elements - Zero or more elements.
        Returns:
        A list containing the given elements in the same order.

      • flatten

        default <U> Stream<U> flatten()
        Description copied from interface: Traversable

        Flattens this Traversable, i.e. unboxes iterable elements. If this Traversable contains elements and iterables of elements of the same type, flattening works as expected.

        Examples:
        • List.of(1, 2, 3).flatten() = List.of(1, 2, 3)
        • List.of(List.of(1), Stream.of(2, 3)).flatten() = List.of(1, 2, 3)
        • List.of(1, List.of(2), Stream.of(3, 4)).flatten() = List.of(1, 2, 3, 4)
        Specified by:
        flatten in interface Seq<T>
        Specified by:
        flatten in interface Traversable<T>
        Type Parameters:
        U - new component type (!!UNSAFE!! of(1, 2, 3).map(Object::toString).<Integer> flatten())
        Returns:
        a flattened version of this traversable

      • flatten

        default <U> Stream<U> flatten(Function<T,? extends Iterable<? extends U>> f)
        Description copied from interface: Traversable

        Flattens this Traversable using a function as hint how to obtain iterable elements.

        Examples:
        • List.of(1, 2, 3).flatten(i -> List.of(i)) = List.of(1, 2, 3)
        • List.of(List.of(1), Stream.of(2, 3)).flatten(Function.identity()) = List.of(1, 2, 3)
        • List.of(1, List.of(2), Stream.of(3, 4))
     .flatten(x -> Match
         .caze((Iterable<Integer> ys) -> ys)
         .caze((Integer i) -> List.of(i))
         .apply(x)
     ) = List.of(1, 2, 3, 4)}
        Specified by:

        zipAll in interface Seq<T>

If that is shorter than this Traversable, thatElem values are used to fill the result.
